                     <interp inst="t18260914-332-defend1760" type="age" value="18"></interp>
                  </persName>
             was indicted for <rs id="t18260914-332-off1869" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18260914-332-off1869" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-332-off1869" type="offenceSubcategory" value="pocketpicking"></interp>
               stealing, on the <rs id="t18260914-332-cd1870" type="crimeDate">14th of August</rs>
                     <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-332-off1869 t18260914-332-cd1870"></join>, 4 sovereigns, 2 half-crowns, 2 shillings, and 2 sixpences, the monies of 
                     <persName id="t18260914-332-victim1761" type="victimName">
                        Joseph 
                        Labovitch
                     <interp inst="t18260914-332-victim1761" type="surname" value="Labovitch"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18260914-332-victim1761" type="given" value="Joseph"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18260914-332-victim1761" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-332-off1869 t18260914-332-victim1761"></join>
                     </persName>
                   from his person
            </rs>.</p>
               <p>JOSEPH LABOVITCH. (Through an interpreter.) I live in Brown's-buildings, and am a <rs id="t18260914-332-viclabel1871" type="occupation">licensed-hawker and pedlar</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-332-victim1761 t18260914-332-viclabel1871"></join>. On the 14th of August, about four o'clock in the afternoon, I was in a brick-field, with a box, selling rhubarb; I had a little box, containing four sovereigns, some half-crowns, shillings, and sixpences. The prisoner came out of the field, and cheapened a piece of rhubarb - he told me to wait while he went into the field; I waited on the opposite side of the field, and there was a brook - the prisoner called me, and he laid down some bricks for me to get over, but I went to another place, a little higher, which I could step over; the prisoner then came again, and he pulled the box, which I had across my shoulder - the strap broke, and when the box was on the ground he put his hand in, and took the money out; he ran away: I made a terrible noise, till some persons came to my assistance; I left my box on the ground, and when I came back it was safe, but I have never got my money; I did not see him again till the officer took me to a public-house, where I saw him with many others, and distinguished him - I swear he is the man.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-332-person1762">
                  THOMAS 
                  COPE
               <interp inst="t18260914-332-person1762" type="surname" value="COPE"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-332-person1762" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-332-person1762" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable. On the 14th of August, at a quarter before four o'clock, I met the prosecutor in Lower-road, Islington - he appeared much agitated, and put his hand to his pockets; a gentleman said he had been robbed by the brick-makers; I went to the field, and saw the stool where the prisoner had worked was wet, and a boy there called out, "Whahaak," which is a signal for a person who has done wrong to keep away; I then went to the Green Man public-house with the prosecutor, who put his hand on the prisoner's shoulder, and pointed him out as the man.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-332-person1763">
                  WILLIAM 
                  SLATER
               <interp inst="t18260914-332-person1763" type="surname" value="SLATER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-332-person1763" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-332-person1763" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I work in <placeName id="t18260914-332-crimeloc1872">Mr. Laycock's brickfield</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-332-crimeloc1872" type="placeName" value="Mr. Laycock's brickfield"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18260914-332-crimeloc1872" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18260914-332-off1869 t18260914-332-crimeloc1872"></join>, at the next stool to the prisoner. On the 14th of August, about four o'clock, I saw the prosecutor on the road; the prisoner went over the road, and called to him to come - he seemed afraid, but the prisoner laid down two or three bricks for him to come over, which he did; the prisoner then asked the price of his rhubarb; he said 3s. 6d.,<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="182609140138"></xptr>3s. 3d., and 3s., and the prisoner ran off with it; a man ran after him, and bring it back; I saw the box safe round the prosecutor's neck - he put it down himself, and ran a little way after the prisoner.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I asked the price of the rhubarb, and offered him 2s.; I went to ask a friend if he thought it was worth it, but the prosecutor made such a noise that I was afraid to bring it back, and I sent it back by the moulder.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18260914-332-person1764">
                  SARAH 
                  BAILEY
               <interp inst="t18260914-332-person1764" type="surname" value="BAILEY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-332-person1764" type="given" value="SARAH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18260914-332-person1764" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a brick-maker. I was at the next stool to the prisoner; I saw the prosecutor take the box off his own neck, and go to get the rbubarb back.</p>
               <p>COURT to THOMAS COPE. Q. When the prosecutor pointed out the prisoner, did he say any thing? A. No - but on the road he acknowledged taking the rhubarb, but nothing else.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18260914-332-verdict1873" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18260914-332-verdict1873" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 18.</p>
